# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: kernelization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:kernelization/data-reduction] When information is derived from instrument readings there may also be a transformation from analog to digital form.
[src:kernelization/data-reduction] When the data are already in digital form the 'reduction' of the data typically involves some editing, scaling, encoding, sorting, collating, and producing tabular summaries.
[src:kernelization/data-reduction] When the observations are discrete but the underlying phenomenon is continuous then smoothing and interpolation are often needed.
[src:kernelization/data-reduction] The data reduction is often undertaken in the presence of reading or measurement errors.
[src:kernelization/data-reduction] Some idea of the nature of these errors is needed before the most likely value may be determined.
[src:kernelization/data-reduction] An example in astronomy is the data reduction in the *Kepler* satellite.
[src:kernelization/data-reduction] This satellite records 95-megapixel images once every six seconds, generating dozens of megabytes of data per second, which is orders-of-magnitudes more than the downlink bandwidth of 550 kB/s.
[src:kernelization/data-reduction] The on-board data reduction encompasses co-adding the raw frames for thirty minutes, reducing the bandwidth by a factor of 300.
[src:kernelization/data-reduction] Furthermore, interesting targets are pre-selected and only the relevant pixels are processed, which is 6% of the total.
[src:kernelization/data-reduction] This reduced data is then sent to Earth where it is processed further.
[src:kernelization/data-reduction] Research has also been carried out on the use of data reduction in wearable (wireless) devices for health monitoring and diagnosis applications.
[src:kernelization/data-reduction] For example, in the context of epilepsy diagnosis, data reduction has been used to increase the battery lifetime of a wearable EEG device by selecting and only transmitting EEG data that is relevant for diagnosis and discarding background activity.
[src:kernelization/data-reduction] When dimensionality increases, data becomes increasingly sparse while density and distance between points, critical to clustering and outlier analysis, becomes less meaningful.
[src:kernelization/data-reduction] Dimensionality reduction helps reduce noise in the data and allows for easier visualization, such as the example below where 3-dimensional data is transformed into 2 dimensions to show hidden parts.
[src:kernelization/data-reduction] One method of dimensionality reduction is wavelet transform, in which data is transformed to preserve relative distance between objects at different levels of resolution, and is often used for image compression.
[src:kernelization/data-reduction] This method of data reduction reduces the data volume by choosing alternate, smaller forms of data representation.
[src:kernelization/data-reduction] Numerosity reduction can be split into 2 groups: parametric and non-parametric methods.
[src:kernelization/data-reduction] Parametric methods (regression, for example) assume the data fits some model, estimate model parameters, store only the parameters, and discard the data.
[src:kernelization/data-reduction] One example of this is in the image below, where the volume of data to be processed is reduced based on more specific criteria.
[src:kernelization/data-reduction] Another example would be a log-linear model, obtaining a value at a point in m-D space as the product on appropriate marginal subspaces.
[src:kernelization/data-reduction] Non-parametric methods do not assume models, some examples being histograms, clustering, sampling, etc.
[src:kernelization/data-reduction] Data reduction can be obtained by assuming a statistical model for the data.
[src:kernelization/data-reduction] Classical principles of data reduction include sufficiency, likelihood, conditionality and equivariance.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] In graph theory, a **dominating set** for a graph *G* is a subset *D* of its vertices, such that any vertex of *G* is in *D*, or has a neighbor in *D*.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] The **domination number** γ(*G*) is the number of vertices in a smallest dominating set for G.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] The **dominating set problem** concerns testing whether γ(*G*) ≤ *K* for a given graph G and input K; it is a classical NP-complete decision problem in computational complexity theory.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Therefore it is believed that there may be no efficient algorithm that can compute γ(*G*) for all graphs *G*.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] However, there are efficient approximation algorithms, as well as efficient exact algorithms for certain graph classes.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Dominating sets are of practical interest in several areas.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] In wireless networking, dominating sets are used to find efficient routes within ad-hoc mobile networks.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] They have also been used in document summarization, and in designing secure systems for electrical grids.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Dominating sets are closely related to independent sets: an independent set is also a dominating set if and only if it is a maximal independent set, so any maximal independent set in a graph is necessarily also a minimal dominating set.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Given an undirected graph *G* = (*V*, *E*), a subset of vertices $D\subseteq V$ is called a **dominating set** if for every vertex $u\in V\setminus D$ , there is a vertex $v\in D$ such that $\{u,v\}\in E$ .
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Every graph has at least one dominating set: if $D=V=$ the set of all vertices, then by definition *D* is a dominating set, since there is no vertex $u\in V\setminus D$ .
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] A more interesting challenge is to find small dominating sets.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] The **domination number** of *G* is defined as: $\gamma (G):=\min\{|D|:D{\text{ is a dominating set of }}G\}$ .
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] The domination problem was studied from the 1950s onwards, but the rate of research on domination significantly increased in the mid-1970s.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] In 1972, Richard Karp proved the set cover problem to be NP-complete.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] This had immediate implications for the dominating set problem, as there are straightforward vertex to set and edge to non-disjoint-intersection bijections between the two problems.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] This proved the dominating set problem to be NP-complete as well.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] The set cover problem is a well-known NP-hard problem – the decision version of set covering was one of Karp's 21 NP-complete problems.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] There exist a pair of polynomial-time L-reductions between the minimum dominating set problem and the set cover problem.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] These reductions (see below) show that an efficient algorithm for the minimum dominating set problem would provide an efficient algorithm for the set cover problem, and vice versa.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Moreover, the reductions preserve the approximation ratio: for any α, a polynomial-time α-approximation algorithm for minimum dominating sets would provide a polynomial-time α-approximation algorithm for the set cover problem and vice versa.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Both problems are in fact Log-APX-complete.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] The approximability of set covering is also well understood: a logarithmic approximation factor can be found by using a simple greedy algorithm, and finding a sublogarithmic approximation factor is NP-hard.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] More specifically, the greedy algorithm provides a factor 1 + log|*V*| approximation of a minimum dominating set, and no polynomial time algorithm can achieve an approximation factor better than *c* log|*V*| for some *c* > 0 unless P = NP.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] The following two reductions show that the minimum dominating set problem and the set cover problem are equivalent under L-reductions: given an instance of one problem, we can construct an equivalent instance of the other problem.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Given a graph *G* = (*V*, *E*) with *V* = {1, 2, ..., *n*}, construct a set cover instance (*U*, *S*) as follows: the universe U is V, and the family of subsets is *S* = {*S*1, *S*2, ..., *S**n*} such that Sv consists of the vertex v and all vertices adjacent to v in G.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Now if D is a dominating set for G, then *C* = {*S**v* : *v* ∈ *D*} is a feasible solution of the set cover problem, with |*C*| = |*D*|.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Conversely, if *C* = {*S**v* : *v* ∈ *D*} is a feasible solution of the set cover problem, then D is a dominating set for G, with |*D*| = |*C*|.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Hence the size of a minimum dominating set for G equals the size of a minimum set cover for (*U*, *S*).
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Furthermore, there is a simple algorithm that maps a dominating set to a set cover of the same size and vice versa.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] In particular, an efficient α-approximation algorithm for set covering provides an efficient α-approximation algorithm for minimum dominating sets.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Let (*S*, *U*) be an instance of the set cover problem with the universe U and the family of subsets *S* = {*S**i* : *i* ∈ *I*}; we assume that U and the index set I are disjoint.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Construct a graph *G* = (*V*, *E*) as follows: the set of vertices is *V* = *I* ∪ *U*, there is an edge {*i*, *j*} ∈ *E* between each pair *i*, *j* ∈ *I*, and there is also an edge {*i*, *u*} for each *i* ∈ *I* and *u* ∈ *S**i*.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] That is, G is a split graph: I is a clique and U is an independent set.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Second, since D must be nonempty, each *i* ∈ *I* is adjacent to a vertex in D.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Conversely, let D be a dominating set for G.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Then it is possible to construct another dominating set X such that |*X*| ≤ |*D*| and *X* ⊆ *I*: simply replace each *u* ∈ *D* ∩ *U* by a neighbour *i* ∈ *I* of u.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] If the graph has maximum degree Δ, then the greedy approximation algorithm finds an *O*(log Δ)-approximation of a minimum dominating set.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Also, let dg be the cardinality of dominating set obtained using greedy approximation then following relation holds, $d_{g}\leq N+1-{\sqrt {2M+1}}$ , where N is number of nodes and M is number of edges in given undirected graph.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] For fixed Δ, this qualifies as a dominating set for APX membership; in fact, it is APX-complete.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] The problem admits a polynomial-time approximation scheme (PTAS) for special cases such as unit disk graphs and planar graphs.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] A minimum dominating set can be found in linear time in series–parallel graphs.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] A minimum dominating set of an n-vertex graph can be found in time *O*(2*n**n*) by inspecting all vertex subsets.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Fomin, Grandoni & Kratsch (2009) show how to find a minimum dominating set in time *O*(1.5137*n*) and exponential space, and in time *O*(1.5264*n*) and polynomial space.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] A faster algorithm, using *O*(1.5048*n*) time was found by van Rooij, Nederlof & van Dijk (2009), who also show that the number of minimum dominating sets can be computed in this time.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] The number of minimal dominating sets is at most 1.7159*n* and all such sets can be listed in time *O*(1.7159*n*).
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Finding a dominating set of size k plays a central role in the theory of parameterized complexity.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] It is the most well-known problem complete for the class W[2] and used in many reductions to show intractability of other problems.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] In particular, the problem is not fixed-parameter tractable in the sense that no algorithm with running time *f*(*k*)*n*O(1) for any function f exists unless the W-hierarchy collapses to FPT=W[2].
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] On the other hand, if the input graph is planar, the problem remains NP-hard, but a fixed-parameter algorithm is known.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] In fact, the problem has a kernel of size linear in k, and running times that are exponential in √*k* and cubic in n may be obtained by applying dynamic programming to a branch-decomposition of the kernel.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] The complementary set to a dominating set, a nonblocker, can be found by a fixed-parameter algorithm on any graph.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] An **independent dominating set** is a dominating set that is also an independent set, or equivalently, a maximal independent set.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] The **independent domination number** $i(G)$ is the minimum size of an independent dominating set of G.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Since the minimum is taken over fewer sets, $\gamma (G)\leq i(G)$ for all graphs G, and the inequality can be strict.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Equality holds for claw-free graphs; since every line graph is claw-free, it follows that the minimum maximal matching and the minimum edge dominating set of any graph have the same size.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] An **independence dominating set** of a graph G is a set that dominates every independent set of G .
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] The **independence domination number** $i\gamma (G)$ is the maximum, over all independent sets A of G , of the smallest set dominating A .
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Dominating only independent sets requires potentially fewer vertices than dominating all vertices, so $i\gamma (G)\leq \gamma (G)$ for all graphs G , and the ratio $\gamma (G)/i\gamma (G)$ can be arbitrarily large.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] A **connected dominating set** is a dominating set that is also connected.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] If S is a connected dominating set, one can form a spanning tree of G in which S forms the set of non-leaf vertices of the tree; conversely, if T is any spanning tree in a graph with more than two vertices, the non-leaf vertices of T form a connected dominating set.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Therefore, finding minimum connected dominating sets is equivalent to finding spanning trees with the maximum possible number of leaves.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] A **total dominating set** is a set of vertices such that all vertices in the graph, *including* the vertices in the dominating set themselves, have a neighbor in the dominating set.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] That is: for every vertex $u\in V$ , there is a vertex $v\in D$ such that $\{u,v\}\in E$ .
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Figure (c) above shows a dominating set that is a connected dominating set and a total dominating set; the examples in figures (a) and (b) are neither.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] In contrast to a simple dominating set, a total dominating set may not exist.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] For example, a graph with one or more vertices and no edges does not have a total dominating set.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] The **total domination number** $\gamma ^{\text{total}}(G)$ is defined as the minimum size of a total dominating set of *G*; obviously, $\gamma ^{\text{total}}(G)\geq \gamma (G)$ .
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] A **dominating edge-set** is a set of edges (vertex pairs) whose union is a dominating set; such a set may not exist (for example, a graph with one or more vertices and no edges does not have it).
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] If it exists, then the union of all its edges is a total dominating set.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Therefore, the smallest size of an edge-dominating set is at least $\gamma ^{\text{total}}(G)/2$ .
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] In contrast, an **edge-dominating set** is a set D of edges, such that every edge not in D is adjacent to at least one edge in D ; such a set always exists (for example, the set of all edges is an edge-dominating set).
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] A **k-dominating set** is a set of vertices such that each vertex not in the set has at least k neighbors in the set (a standard dominating set is a 1-dominating set).
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Similarly, a **k-tuple dominating set** is a set of vertices such that each vertex in the graph has at least k neighbors in the set (a total dominating set is a 1-tuple dominating set).
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] An (1 + log *n*)-approximation of a minimum k-tuple dominating set can be found in polynomial time.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Every graph admits a k-dominating set (for example, the set of all vertices); but only graphs with minimum degree *k* − 1 admit a k-tuple dominating set.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] However, even if the graph admits k-tuple dominating set, a minimum k-tuple dominating set can be nearly k times as large as a minimum k-dominating set for the same graph; An (1.7 + log Δ)-approximation of a minimum k-dominating set can be found in polynomial time as well.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] A **fractional dominating set** is defined from a *fractional dominating function*, a function $f:V(G)\to [0,1]$ such that for every vertex $v\in V$ , the sum of f over the closed neighborhood $N[v]$ is at least 1.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] The **fractional domination number** $\gamma _{f}(G)$ is the minimum total weight (sum of all vertex values) of such a function, and satisfies $\gamma _{f}(G)\leq \gamma (G)$ .
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] For a k -regular graph with n vertices ( $k\geq 1$ ), the fractional domination number equals $n/(k+1)$ .
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] A **star-dominating set** is a subset D of V such that, for every vertex v in V , the star of v (the set of edges adjacent to v ) intersects the star of some vertex in D .
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Clearly, if G has isolated vertices then it has no star-dominating sets (since the star of isolated vertices is empty).
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] If G has no isolated vertices, then every dominating set is a star-dominating set and vice versa.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] The distinction between star-domination and usual domination is more substantial when their fractional variants are considered.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] A **domatic partition** is a partition of the vertices into disjoint dominating sets.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] The domatic number is the maximum size of a domatic partition.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] An **eternal dominating set** is a dynamic version of domination in which a vertex v in dominating set D is chosen and replaced with a neighbor u ( u is not in D ) such that the modified D is also a dominating set and this process can be repeated over any infinite sequence of choices of vertices v .
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] An **efficient dominating set** (also called an e.d. set or independent perfect dominating set) is a dominating set with the additional property that every vertex in the graph is dominated by **exactly one** vertex in the set.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] A **Roman dominating set** is defined through a *Roman dominating function*, which assigns to each vertex a value from $\{0,1,2\}$ such that every vertex assigned 0 is adjacent to at least one vertex assigned 2.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] The **Roman domination number** $\gamma _{R}(G)$ is the minimum sum of all vertex values over all such functions.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] The concept is inspired by a defensive strategy of the Roman Empire, where vertices represent cities and values represent stationed legions.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] For any graph G , $\gamma (G)\leq \gamma _{R}(G)\leq 2\gamma (G)$ , with the lower bound achieved only by the empty graph.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] A **global dominating set** is a dominating set of a graph G that is also a dominating set of the complement graph ${\overline {G}}$ .
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] The **global domination number** $\gamma _{g}(G)$ is the minimum cardinality of a global dominating set.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Equivalently, a dominating set S is a global dominating set if and only if for each vertex $v\in V-S$ , there exists a vertex $u\in S$ such that u is not adjacent to v .
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] For a graph G with p vertices, $\gamma _{g}(G)=p$ if and only if $G=K_{p}$ or $G={\overline {K_{p}}}$ .
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] A **certified dominating set** is a dominating set in which every vertex in the set has either zero or at least two neighbours outside the set.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] The **certified domination number** $\gamma _{\text{cer}}(G)$ is the minimum size of a certified dominating set.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] Clearly, $\gamma _{\text{cer}}(G)\geq \gamma (G)$ , and equality holds whenever the graph has no *weak support vertex* (in particular, when $\delta (G)\geq 2$ ).
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] For a connected graph, $\gamma _{\text{cer}}(G)\leq 2\gamma (G)$ .
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] A **paired dominating set** of a graph $G=(V,E)$ is a dominating set S of vertices such that the induced subgraph $G[S]$ contains at least one perfect matching.
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] The **paired domination number** $\gamma _{p}(G)$ is the minimum cardinality of a paired dominating set of G .
[src:kernelization/dominating-set] The concept models a situation in which guards are placed at vertices of a graph to dominate (protect) all vertices, with the additional constraint that each guard is assigned another adjacent guard as a backup.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] In graph theory, an **independent set**, **stable set**, **coclique** or **anticlique** is a set of vertices in a graph, no two of which are adjacent.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] That is, it is a set S of vertices such that for every two vertices in S , there is no edge connecting the two.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] Equivalently, each edge in the graph has at most one endpoint in S .
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] A set is independent if and only if it is a clique in the graph's complement.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] The size of an independent set is the number of vertices it contains.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] Independent sets have also been called "internally stable sets", of which "stable set" is a shortening.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] A maximal independent set is an independent set that is not a proper subset of any other independent set.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] A **maximum independent set** is an independent set of largest possible size for a given graph G .
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] This size is called the **independence number** of *G* and is usually denoted by $\alpha (G)$ .
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] The optimization problem of finding such a set is called the **maximum independent set problem.** It is a strongly NP-hard problem.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] As such, it is unlikely that there exists an efficient algorithm for finding a maximum independent set of a graph.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] Every maximum independent set also is maximal, but the converse implication does not necessarily hold.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] A set is independent if and only if it is a clique in the graph’s complement, so the two concepts are complementary.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] In fact, sufficiently large graphs with no large cliques have large independent sets, a theme that is explored in Ramsey theory.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] A set is independent if and only if its complement is a vertex cover.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] Therefore, the sum of the size of the largest independent set $\alpha (G)$ and the size of a minimum vertex cover $\beta (G)$ is equal to the number of vertices in the graph.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] A vertex coloring of a graph G corresponds to a partition of its vertex set into independent subsets.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] Hence the minimal number of colors needed in a vertex coloring, the *chromatic number* $\chi (G)$ , is at least the quotient of the number of vertices in G and the independent number $\alpha (G)$ .
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] In a bipartite graph with no isolated vertices, the number of vertices in a maximum independent set equals the number of edges in a minimum edge covering; this is Kőnig's theorem.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] An independent set that is not a proper subset of another independent set is called *maximal*.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] Every graph contains at most 3*n*/3 maximal independent sets, but many graphs have far fewer.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] The number of maximal independent sets in *n*-vertex cycle graphs is given by the Perrin numbers, and the number of maximal independent sets in *n*-vertex path graphs is given by the Padovan sequence.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] Therefore, both numbers are proportional to powers of 1.324718..., the plastic ratio.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] In computer science, several computational problems related to independent sets have been studied.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] The first three of these problems are all important in practical applications; the independent set decision problem is not, but is necessary in order to apply the theory of NP-completeness to problems related to independent sets.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] The independent set problem and the clique problem are complementary: a clique in *G* is an independent set in the complement graph of *G* and vice versa.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] Therefore, many computational results may be applied equally well to either problem.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] Despite the close relationship between maximum cliques and maximum independent sets in arbitrary graphs, the independent set and clique problems may be very different when restricted to special classes of graphs.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] The maximum independent set problem is NP-hard.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] However, it can be solved more efficiently than the O(*n*2 2*n*) time that would be given by a naive brute force algorithm that examines every vertex subset and checks whether it is an independent set.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] As of 2017 it can be solved in time O(1.1996*n*) using polynomial space.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] When restricted to graphs with maximum degree 3, it can be solved in time O(1.0836*n*).
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] For many classes of graphs, a maximum weight independent set may be found in polynomial time.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] Famous examples are claw-free graphs, *P*5-free graphs and perfect graphs.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] For chordal graphs, a maximum weight independent set can be found in linear time.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] Modular decomposition is a good tool for solving the maximum weight independent set problem; the linear time algorithm on cographs is the basic example for that.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] Another important tool are clique separators as described by Tarjan.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] Kőnig's theorem implies that in a bipartite graph the maximum independent set can be found in polynomial time using a bipartite matching algorithm.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] In general, the maximum independent set problem cannot be approximated to a constant factor in polynomial time (unless P = NP).
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] In fact, Max Independent Set in general is Poly-APX-complete, meaning it is as hard as any problem that can be approximated to a polynomial factor.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] However, there are efficient approximation algorithms for restricted classes of graphs.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] In planar graphs, the maximum independent set may be approximated to within any approximation ratio *c* < 1 in polynomial time; similar polynomial-time approximation schemes exist in any family of graphs closed under taking minors.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] Approximation hardness bounds for such instances were proven in Berman & Karpinski (1999).
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] Indeed, even Max Independent Set on 3-regular 3-edge-colorable graphs is APX-complete.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] An interval graph is a graph in which the nodes are 1-dimensional intervals (e.g. time intervals) and there is an edge between two intervals if and only if they intersect.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] An independent set in an interval graph is just a set of non-overlapping intervals.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] The problem of finding maximum independent sets in interval graphs has been studied, for example, in the context of job scheduling: given a set of jobs that has to be executed on a computer, find a maximum set of jobs that can be executed without interfering with each other.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] This problem can be solved exactly in polynomial time using earliest deadline first scheduling.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] A geometric intersection graph is a graph in which the nodes are geometric shapes and there is an edge between two shapes if and only if they intersect.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] An independent set in a geometric intersection graph is just a set of disjoint (non-overlapping) shapes.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] The problem of finding maximum independent sets in geometric intersection graphs has been studied, for example, in the context of Automatic label placement: given a set of locations in a map, find a maximum set of disjoint rectangular labels near these locations.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] Finding a maximum independent set in intersection graphs is still NP-complete, but it is easier to approximate than the general maximum independent set problem.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] A recent survey can be found in the introduction of Chan & Har-Peled (2012).
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] A *d-claw* in a graph is a set of *d*+1 vertices, one of which (the "center") is connected to the other *d* vertices, but the other d vertices are not connected to each other.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] A *d*-claw-free graph is a graph that does not have a *d*-claw subgraph.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] Consider the algorithm that starts with an empty set, and incrementally adds an arbitrary vertex to it as long as it is not adjacent to any existing vertex.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] In *d*-claw-free graphs, every added vertex invalidates at most *d* − 1 vertices from the maximum independent set; therefore, this trivial algorithm attains a (*d* − 1)-approximation algorithm for the maximum independent set.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] The problem of finding a maximal independent set can be solved in polynomial time by a trivial parallel greedy algorithm .
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] All maximal independent sets can be found in time O(3*n*/3) = O(1.4423*n*).
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] Is there a fully polynomial-time approximation algorithm for the number of independent sets in bipartite graphs?
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] The counting problem #IS asks, given an undirected graph, how many independent sets it contains.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] This problem is intractable, namely, it is ♯P-complete, already on graphs with maximal degree three.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] The problem #BIS, of counting independent sets on bipartite graphs, is also ♯P-complete, already on graphs with maximal degree three.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] It is not known whether #BIS admits a FPRAS.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] The question of counting maximal independent sets has also been studied.
[src:kernelization/independent-set-graph-theory] The maximum independent set and its complement, the minimum vertex cover problem, is involved in proving the computational complexity of many theoretical problems.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] In computer science, a **kernelization** is a technique for designing efficient algorithms that achieve their efficiency by a preprocessing stage in which inputs to the algorithm are replaced by a smaller input, called a "kernel".
[src:kernelization/kernelization] The result of solving the problem on the kernel should either be the same as on the original input, or it should be easy to transform the output on the kernel to the desired output for the original problem.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] Kernelization is often achieved by applying a set of reduction rules that cut away parts of the instance that are easy to handle.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] In parameterized complexity theory, it is often possible to prove that a kernel with guaranteed bounds on the size of a kernel (as a function of some parameter associated to the problem) can be found in polynomial time.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] When this is possible, it results in a fixed-parameter tractable algorithm whose running time is the sum of the (polynomial time) kernelization step and the (non-polynomial but bounded by the parameter) time to solve the kernel.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] Indeed, every problem that can be solved by a fixed-parameter tractable algorithm can be solved by a kernelization algorithm of this type.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] This is also true for approximate kernelization.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] A standard example for a kernelization algorithm is the kernelization of the vertex cover problem by S.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] In this problem, the input is an undirected graph G together with a number k .
[src:kernelization/kernelization] The output is a set of at most k vertices that includes an endpoint of every edge in the graph, if such a set exists, or a failure exception if no such set exists.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] An isolated vertex cannot cover any edges, so in this case v cannot be part of any minimal cover.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] If more than $k^{2}$ edges remain in the graph, and neither of the previous two rules can be applied, then the graph cannot contain a vertex cover of size k .
[src:kernelization/kernelization] For, after eliminating all vertices of degree greater than k , each remaining vertex can only cover at most k edges and a set of k vertices could only cover at most $k^{2}$ edges.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] In this case, the instance may be replaced by an instance with two vertices, one edge, and $k=0$ , which also has no solution.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] An algorithm that applies these rules repeatedly until no more reductions can be made necessarily terminates with a kernel that has at most $k^{2}$ edges and (because each edge has at most two endpoints and there are no isolated vertices) at most $2k^{2}$ vertices.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] This kernelization may be implemented in linear time.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] Once the kernel has been constructed, the vertex cover problem may be solved by a brute force search algorithm that tests whether each subset of the kernel is a cover of the kernel.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] Thus, the vertex cover problem can be solved in time $O(2^{2k^{2}}+n+m)$ for a graph with n vertices and m edges, allowing it to be solved efficiently when k is small even if n and m are both large.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] Although this bound is fixed-parameter tractable, its dependence on the parameter is higher than might be desired.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] More complex kernelization procedures can improve this bound, by finding smaller kernels, at the expense of greater running time in the kernelization step.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] In the vertex cover example, kernelization algorithms are known that produce kernels with at most $2k$ vertices.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] One algorithm that achieves this improved bound exploits the half-integrality of the linear program relaxation of vertex cover due to Nemhauser and Trotter.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] Another kernelization algorithm achieving that bound is based on what is known as the crown reduction rule and uses alternating path arguments.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] The currently best known kernelization algorithm in terms of the number of vertices is due to Lampis (2011) and achieves $2k-c\log k$ vertices for any fixed constant c .
[src:kernelization/kernelization] It is not possible, in this problem, to find a kernel of size $O(\log k)$ , unless P = NP, for such a kernel would lead to a polynomial-time algorithm for the NP-hard vertex cover problem.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] However, much stronger bounds on the kernel size can be proven in this case: unless coNP $\subseteq$ NP/poly (believed unlikely by complexity theorists), for every $\epsilon >0$ it is impossible in polynomial time to find kernels with $O(k^{2-\epsilon })$ edges.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] It is unknown for vertex cover whether kernels with $(2-\epsilon )k$ vertices for some $\epsilon >0$ would have any unlikely complexity-theoretic consequences.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] In the literature, there is no clear consensus on how kernelization should be formally defined and there are subtle differences in the uses of that expression.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] In the notation of Downey & Fellows (1999), a *parameterized problem* is a subset $L\subseteq \Sigma ^{*}\times \mathbb {N}$ describing a decision problem.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] The output $(x',k')$ of kernelization is called a kernel.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] In this general context, the *size* of the string $x'$ just refers to its length.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] Some authors prefer to use the number of vertices or the number of edges as the size measure in the context of graph problems.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] In the notation of Flum & Grohe (2006, p.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] 4), a *parameterized problem* consists of a decision problem $L\subseteq \Sigma ^{*}$ and a function $\kappa :\Sigma ^{*}\to \mathbb {N}$ , the parameterization.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] The *parameter* of an instance x is the number $\kappa (x)$ .
[src:kernelization/kernelization] Note that in this notation, the bound on the size of y implies that the parameter of y is also bounded by a function in k .
[src:kernelization/kernelization] The function f is often referred to as the size of the kernel.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] If $f=k^{O(1)}$ , it is said that L admits a polynomial kernel.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] Similarly, for $f={O(k)}$ , the problem admits linear kernel.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] A problem is fixed-parameter tractable if and only if it is kernelizable and decidable.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] That a kernelizable and decidable problem is fixed-parameter tractable can be seen from the definition above: First the kernelization algorithm, which runs in time $O(|x|^{c})$ for some c, is invoked to generate a kernel of size $f(k)$ .
[src:kernelization/kernelization] The kernel is then solved by the algorithm that proves that the problem is decidable.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] The total running time of this procedure is $g(f(k))+O(|x|^{c})$ , where $g(n)$ is the running time for the algorithm used to solve the kernels.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] Since $g(f(k))$ is computable, e.g. by using the assumption that $f(k)$ is computable and testing all possible inputs of length $f(k)$ , this implies that the problem is fixed-parameter tractable.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] The other direction, that a fixed-parameter tractable problem is kernelizable and decidable is a bit more involved.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] Assume that the question is non-trivial, meaning that there is at least one instance that is in the language, called $I_{yes}$ , and at least one instance that is not in the language, called $I_{no}$ ; otherwise, replacing any instance by the empty string is a valid kernelization.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] Assume also that the problem is fixed-parameter tractable, i.e., it has an algorithm that runs in at most $f(k)\cdot |x|^{c}$ steps on instances $(x,k)$ , for some constant c and some function $f(k)$ .
[src:kernelization/kernelization] To kernelize an input, run this algorithm on the given input for at most $|x|^{c+1}$ steps.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] If it terminates with an answer, use that answer to select either $I_{yes}$ or $I_{no}$ as the kernel.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] If, instead, it exceeds the $|x|^{c+1}$ bound on the number of steps without terminating, then return $(x,k)$ itself as the kernel.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] Because $(x,k)$ is only returned as a kernel for inputs with $f(k)\cdot |x|^{c}>|x|^{c+1}$ , it follows that the size of the kernel produced in this way is at most $\max\{|I_{yes}|,|I_{no}|,f(k)\}$ .
[src:kernelization/kernelization] This size bound is computable, by the assumption from fixed-parameter tractability that $f(k)$ is computable.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] While the parameter k in the examples above is chosen as the size of the desired solution, this is not necessary.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] It is also possible to choose a structural complexity measure of the input as the parameter value, leading to so-called structural parameterizations.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] This approach is fruitful for instances whose solution size is large, but for which some other complexity measure is bounded.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] For example, the *feedback vertex number* of an undirected graph G is defined as the minimum cardinality of a set of vertices whose removal makes G acyclic.
[src:kernelization/kernelization] The kernelization algorithm therefore guarantees that instances with a small feedback vertex number k are reduced to small instances.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] In computer science, **parameterized complexity** is a branch of computational complexity theory that focuses on classifying computational problems according to their inherent difficulty with respect to *multiple* parameters of the input or output.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] The complexity of a problem is then measured as a function of those parameters.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] This allows the classification of NP-hard problems on a finer scale than in the classical setting, where the complexity of a problem is only measured as a function of the number of bits in the input.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] This appears to have been first demonstrated in Gurevich, Stockmeyer & Vishkin (1984).
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] The first systematic work on parameterized complexity was done by Downey & Fellows (1999).
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] However, some problems can be solved by algorithms that are exponential only in the size of a fixed parameter while polynomial in the size of the input.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Under the assumption that P ≠ NP, there exist many natural problems that require super-polynomial running time when complexity is measured in terms of the input size only but that are computable in a time that is polynomial in the input size and exponential or worse in a parameter k.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Hence, if k is fixed at a small value and the growth of the function over k is relatively small then such problems can still be considered "tractable" despite their traditional classification as "intractable".
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Such an algorithm is called a fixed-parameter tractable (FPT) algorithm, because the problem can be solved efficiently (i.e., in polynomial time) for constant values of the fixed parameter.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] A parameterized problem that allows for such an FPT algorithm is said to be a **fixed-parameter tractable** problem and belongs to the class FPT, and the early name of the theory of parameterized complexity was **fixed-parameter tractability**.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Many problems have the following form: given an object x and a nonnegative integer k, does x have some property that depends on k?
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] For instance, for the vertex cover problem, the parameter can be the number of vertices in the cover.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] In many applications, for example when modelling error correction, one can assume the parameter to be "small" compared to the total input size.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Then it is challenging to find an algorithm that is exponential *only* in k, and not in the input size.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] In this way, parameterized complexity can be seen as *two-dimensional* complexity theory.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] when its parameter is the size of the solution to the problem.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] For example, there is an algorithm that solves the vertex cover problem in $O(kn+1.274^{k})$ time, where n is the number of vertices and k is the size of the vertex cover.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] This means that vertex cover is fixed-parameter tractable with the size of the solution as the parameter (its natural parameter).
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] The class **FPL** (fixed parameter linear) is the class of problems solvable in time $f(k)\cdot |x|$ for some computable function f.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] An example is the Boolean satisfiability problem, parameterised by the number of variables.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] A given formula of size m with k variables can be checked by brute force in time $O(2^{k}m)$ .
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] A vertex cover of size k in a graph of order n can be found in time $O(2^{k}n)$ , so the vertex cover problem is also in FPL.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] An example of a problem that is thought not to be in FPT is graph coloring parameterised by the number of colors.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] It is known that 3-coloring is NP-hard, and an algorithm for graph k-coloring in time $f(k)n^{O(1)}$ for $k=3$ would run in polynomial time in the size of the input.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Thus, if graph coloring parameterised by the number of colors were in FPT, then P = NP.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] There are a number of alternative definitions of FPT.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] For example, the running-time requirement can be replaced by $f(k)+|x|^{O(1)}$ .
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Also, a parameterised problem is in FPT if it has a so-called kernel.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Kernelization is a preprocessing technique that reduces the original instance to its "hard kernel", a possibly much smaller instance that is equivalent to the original instance but has a size that is bounded by a function in the parameter.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] FPT is closed under a parameterised notion of reductions called ***fpt-reductions***.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Obviously, FPT contains all polynomial-time computable problems.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Moreover, it contains all optimisation problems in NP that allow an efficient polynomial-time approximation scheme (EPTAS).
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] These problems are called slicewise polynomial, in the sense that each "slice" of fixed *k* has a polynomial-time algorithm, although with a possibly different exponent for each *k*.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Compare this with FPT, which merely allows a different constant prefactor for each value of k.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] XP strictly contains FPT by diagonalization.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] A problem is **para-NP-hard** if it is ${\textsf {NP}}$ -hard already for a constant value of the parameter.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] That is, there is a "slice" of fixed k that is ${\textsf {NP}}$ -hard.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] A parameterized problem that is ${\textsf {para-NP}}$ -hard cannot belong to the class ${\textsf {XP}}$ , unless ${\textsf {P}}={\textsf {NP}}$ .
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] A classic example of a ${\textsf {para-NP}}$ -hard parameterized problem is graph coloring, parameterized by the number k of colors, which is already ${\textsf {NP}}$ -hard for $k=3$ (see Graph coloring#Computational complexity).
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] In the parameterized complexity theory, there are some hierarchies of complexity classes.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Each such class is closed under fpt-reduction.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] The most important ones are the ***W* hierarchy** and the ***A* hierarchy**.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] In general, there are two ways to define a complexity class: machine-theoretically and logically.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] In machine theory, a class is defined as the set of decision problems solvable by a class of machines.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] In logic, a class is defined as the set of decision problems definable by a class of logical formulas.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] The **Hamming weight** (**weight** for short) of a binary string is the number of ones appearing in it.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] A Boolean circuit is an acyclic directed graph where the nodes are one of the following gates: AND, OR, NOT.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] A small gate is a gate with fan-in 0, 1, or 2.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] The **weft** is the largest number of big gates achievable on any path from an input to the output.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] The **depth** is the largest number of gates (small or big) achievable on any path from an input to the output.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] A Boolean circuit is **monotone** iff it uses no NOT gate.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] A Boolean circuit is **antimonotone** iff it is of the form $\phi (\neg x_{1},\dots ,\neg x_{n})$ where $x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}$ are all its inputs, and $\phi$ is monotone.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] we define $\operatorname {p-MC} (\Gamma )$ to be the **parameterized model checking** problem for this tuple.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Here we see that "W" stands for "weight".
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Note that in the above definition, $w,d$ are independent of $(x,k)$ , but the circuit itself depends on $(x,k)$ , and may change if one changes either x or k .
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] A **normalized circuit** of weft *w* and depth *d* is a circuit, where the first $d-w$ layers contain only small gates, and the last w layers contain alternating big gates of AND and OR.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] One can iterate the associative laws and de Morgan distribution laws to normalize the circuit in fpt-time.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Therefore, without loss of generality, we can consider only normalized circuits.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Model-theoretically, the class *W[t]* is defined as the class of problems fpt-reducible to $\operatorname {p-MC} (\Sigma _{t,1})$ .
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] While the *W* hierarchy is a hierarchy contained in NP, the *A* hierarchy more closely mimics the polynomial-time hierarchy from classical complexity.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Machine-theoretically, the A hierarchy of problems are defined as problems that are fpt-reducible to computations by certain kinds of alternating Turing machines.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Model-theoretically, the class *A[t]* is defined as the class of problems fpt-reducible to $\operatorname {p-MC} (\Sigma _{t})$ .
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] For example, the *k*-clique problem can be specified as a model checking problem.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] The language has a single binary relation E , where $E(x,y)$ means " $x,y$ share an edge".
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Then, a finite model A is a graph, and it has a *k*-clique iff $A\models \phi _{k}$ , where $\phi _{k}:=\exists x_{1:k},\bigwedge _{1\leq i<j\leq n}E(x_{i},x_{j})$ This shows that the *k*-clique problem is in $A[1]$ .
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] A problem is ***A[i]*-complete** if it is *A[i]*, and any *A[i]* problem fpt-reduces to it.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Intuitively, problems in W[1] class can be interpreted of the form: Is there an object of size *k* with a certain locally-checkable property?
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] That is, a big AND over many OR of fan-in 2.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Note that the plain nonblocker problem is FPT.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Note on the nondeterministic Turing machine.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] The machine may be specified by one of any of the standard formulations.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] One usually considers the one-tape Turing machine, but the short Turing machine problem remains *W[1]* even if we allow with *f*(*k*) tapes and even *f*(*k*) of *f*(*k*)-dimensional tapes, but even with this extension, the restriction to *f*(*k*) tape alphabet size is FPT.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Crucially, because the machine *M* itself is part of the problem input, the input size *n* is bigger than the number of states of *M*.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] In this way, the Turing machine can take one of n possible computation paths per step, accessing $n^{O(k)}$ steps in total within time *k*.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Thus, we see that *W[1]* is not obviously contained within *FPT*.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] The independent set problem can be encoded thus.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Given each graph $(V,E)$ , its independent set problem is encoded by the following weft-1 Boolean circuit: $\Phi _{\text{IS}}(V,E):=\bigwedge _{\{u,v\}\in E}(\neg x_{u}\lor \neg x_{v})$ where E is the set of edges in the graph.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] The graph has an independent set of size *k* iff there is a weight-*k* input to its Boolean circuit, such that it outputs 1.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] The clique problem can be coded as $\Phi _{\text{clique}}(V,E):=\bigwedge _{\{u,v\}\subset V,u\neq v,\{u,v\}\not \in E}(\neg x_{u}\lor \neg x_{v})$ It checks that any pair vertices that don't make an edge cannot be chosen, so any chosen set of vertices is forced to be a clique.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] The short Turing machine problem can be converted to a Boolean formula using the same proof idea as of the Cook–Levin theorem, which shows SAT is NP-complete by coding Turing machine computational traces as Boolean formulas.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Of the indices, time *t* and tape position *p* range over *1:k*, The ranges of the indices to the Turing machine state *i, j*, transition *m*, and symbols *a, b* are determined by the description of the machine M, but they are both bounded within *1:n*.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] A computational trace through the Turing machine is then fully specified by setting *k* variables of $s_{t,i,j,a,b}$ to True to indicate the Turing machine state transitions at each time, and setting $k^{2}$ variables of $y_{t,p,a,b}$ to True to indicate the tape state transition at each time.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] This reduces the short Turing machine problem to a problem of finding a weight- $(k+k^{2})$ satisfying assignment to a weft-1, depth-2, antimonotone Boolean circuit.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] The dominating set problem has formula $\Psi _{\text{dom}}(V,E)=\bigwedge _{u\in V}\bigvee _{v\in \operatorname {Neighbor} [u]}x_{v}$ .
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Some problems are known to be *W[i]*-complete, though they are in a computationally generic form, and are usually studied within parameterized complexity theory itself.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Empirically, as of 2013, almost all naturally-occurring parameterized problems that they have studied, turned out to be *W[0]*-complete, *W[1]*-complete, or *W[2]*-complete.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] These problems are essentially "artificial", in that they are not studied except within the context of parameterized complexity.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] It contains *W[SAT]*, since a Boolean formula can be efficiently converted to a Boolean circuit.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Note that the opposite is not true in general, since the equivalent Boolean formula to a Boolean circuit may be necessarily exponentially larger than the circuit.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Equivalently, it is the class of problems that can be decided by a nondeterministic $h(k)\cdot {|x|}^{O(1)}$ -time Turing machine that makes at most $O(f(k)\cdot \log n)$ nondeterministic choices in the computation on $(x,k)$ (a *k*-restricted Turing machine).
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] It is known that FPT is contained in W[P], and the inclusion is believed to be strict.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] However, resolving this issue would imply a solution to the P versus NP problem.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] The *W** hierarchy is similar to the *W* hierarchy, but it parameterizes depth, rather than holding it constant.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] One can interpret this as a 2-player game, with the first player trying to make the circuit output True, and the second player trying to make the circuit output False.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] The first player makes a move by setting exactly $k_{1}$ inputs of $I_{1}$ to True and the others to False, then the second player makes a move on $I_{2}$ , etc.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] The circuit is under alternating weight- $(k_{1},\dots ,k_{r})$ conditions iff player 1 has a winning strategy.
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] It turns out that the hierarchy collapses: $AW[1]=AW[2]=\cdots$ .
[src:kernelization/parameterized-complexity] Thus, the literature writes just a common symbol for them: $AW[\ast ]:=AW[1]=AW[2]=\cdots$ .
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] In graph theory, a **vertex cover** (sometimes **node cover**) of a graph is a set of vertices that includes at least one endpoint of every edge of the graph.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] In computer science, the problem of finding a **minimum vertex cover** is a classical optimization problem.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] It is NP-hard, so it cannot be solved by a polynomial-time algorithm if P ≠ NP.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] Moreover, it is hard to approximate – it cannot be approximated up to a factor smaller than 2 if the unique games conjecture is true.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] On the other hand, it has several simple 2-factor approximations.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] It is a typical example of an NP-hard optimization problem that has an approximation algorithm.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] Its decision version, the **vertex cover problem**, was one of Karp's 21 NP-complete problems and is therefore a classical NP-complete problem in computational complexity theory.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] Furthermore, the vertex cover problem is fixed-parameter tractable and a central problem in parameterized complexity theory.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] The minimum vertex cover problem can be formulated as a half-integral, linear program whose dual linear program is the maximum matching problem.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] Vertex cover problems have been generalized to hypergraphs, see *Vertex cover in hypergraphs*.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] Formally, a vertex cover $V'$ of an undirected graph $G=(V,E)$ is a subset of V such that $(uv\in E)\Rightarrow (u\in V'\lor v\in V')$ , that is to say it is a set of vertices $V'$ where every edge has at least one endpoint in the vertex cover $V'$ .
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] Such a set is said to *cover* the edges of G .
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] The upper figure shows two examples of vertex covers, with some vertex cover $V'$ marked in red.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] A *minimum vertex cover* is a vertex cover of smallest possible size.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] The vertex cover number $\tau$ is the size of a minimum vertex cover, i.e. $\tau =|V'|$ .
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] The lower figure shows examples of minimum vertex covers in the previous graphs.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] The **minimum vertex cover problem** is the optimization problem of finding a smallest vertex cover in a given graph.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] They are equivalent under polynomial-time reduction by using binary search.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] The vertex cover problem is an NP-complete problem: it was one of Karp's 21 NP-complete problems.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] It is often used in computational complexity theory as a starting point for NP-hardness proofs.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] Assume that every vertex has an associated cost of $c(v)\geq 0$ .
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] The (weighted) minimum vertex cover problem can be formulated as the following integer linear program (ILP).
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] This ILP belongs to the more general class of ILPs for covering problems.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] The integrality gap of this ILP is 2 , so its relaxation (allowing each variable to be in the interval from 0 to 1, rather than requiring the variables to be only 0 or 1) gives a factor- 2 approximation algorithm for the minimum vertex cover problem.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] Furthermore, the linear programming relaxation of that ILP is *half-integral*, that is, there exists an optimal solution for which each entry $x_{v}$ is either 0, 1/2, or 1.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] A 2-approximate vertex cover can be obtained from this fractional solution by selecting the subset of vertices whose variables are nonzero.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] The decision variant of the vertex cover problem is NP-complete, which means it is unlikely that there is an efficient algorithm to solve it exactly for arbitrary graphs.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] NP-completeness can be proven by reduction from 3-satisfiability or, as Karp did, by reduction from the clique problem.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] Vertex cover remains NP-complete even in cubic graphs and even in planar graphs of degree at most 3.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] For bipartite graphs, the equivalence between vertex cover and maximum matching described by Kőnig's theorem allows the bipartite vertex cover problem to be solved in polynomial time.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] For tree graphs, an algorithm finds a minimal vertex cover in polynomial time by finding the first leaf in the tree and adding its parent to the minimal vertex cover, then deleting the leaf and parent and all associated edges and continuing repeatedly until no edges remain in the tree.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] An exhaustive search algorithm can solve the problem in time 2*k**n**O*(1), where *k* is the size of the vertex cover.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] Vertex cover is therefore fixed-parameter tractable, and if we are only interested in small *k*, we can solve the problem in polynomial time.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] One algorithmic technique that works here is called *bounded search tree algorithm*, and its idea is to repeatedly choose some vertex and recursively branch, with two cases at each step: place either the current vertex or all its neighbours into the vertex cover.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] The algorithm for solving vertex cover that achieves the best asymptotic dependence on the parameter runs in time $O(1.2738^{k}+(k\cdot n))$ .
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] The klam value of this time bound (an estimate for the largest parameter value that could be solved in a reasonable amount of time) is approximately 190.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] That is, unless additional algorithmic improvements can be found, this algorithm is suitable only for instances whose vertex cover number is 190 or less.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] Under reasonable complexity-theoretic assumptions, namely the exponential time hypothesis, the running time cannot be improved to 2*o*(*k*), even when n is $O(k)$ .
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] However, for planar graphs, and more generally, for graphs excluding some fixed graph as a minor, a vertex cover of size *k* can be found in time *$2^{O({\sqrt {k}})}n^{O(1)}$*, i.e., the problem is subexponential fixed-parameter tractable.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] This algorithm is again optimal, in the sense that, under the exponential time hypothesis, no algorithm can solve vertex cover on planar graphs in time *$2^{o({\sqrt {k}})}n^{O(1)}$*.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] One can find a factor-2 approximation by repeatedly taking *both* endpoints of an edge into the vertex cover, then removing them from the graph.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] Put otherwise, we find a maximal matching *M* with a greedy algorithm and construct a vertex cover *C* that consists of all endpoints of the edges in *M*.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] In the following figure, a maximal matching *M* is marked with red, and the vertex cover *C* is marked with blue.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] The set *C* constructed this way is a vertex cover: suppose that an edge *e* is not covered by *C*; then *M* ∪ {*e*} is a matching and *e* ∉ *M*, which is a contradiction with the assumption that *M* is maximal.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] Furthermore, if *e* = {*u*, *v*} ∈ *M*, then any vertex cover – including an optimal vertex cover – must contain *u* or *v* (or both); otherwise the edge *e* is not covered.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] That is, an optimal cover contains at least *one* endpoint of each edge in *M*; in total, the set *C* is at most 2 times as large as the optimal vertex cover.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] This simple algorithm was discovered independently by Fanica Gavril and Mihalis Yannakakis.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] More involved techniques show that there are approximation algorithms with a slightly better approximation factor.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] For example, an approximation algorithm with an approximation factor of ${\textstyle 2-\Theta \left(1/{\sqrt {\log |V|}}\right)}$ is known.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] The problem can be approximated with an approximation factor $2/(1+\delta )$ in $\delta$ - dense graphs.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] No better constant-factor approximation algorithm than the above one is known.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] The minimum vertex cover problem is APX-complete, that is, it cannot be approximated arbitrarily well unless **P** = **NP**.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] Using techniques from the PCP theorem, Dinur and Safra proved in 2005 that minimum vertex cover cannot be approximated within a factor of 1.3606 for any sufficiently large vertex degree unless **P** = **NP**.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] Later, the factor was improved to ${\sqrt {2}}-\epsilon$ for any $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] Moreover, if the unique games conjecture is true then minimum vertex cover cannot be approximated within any constant factor better than 2.
[src:kernelization/vertex-cover] Although finding the minimum-size vertex cover is equivalent to finding the maximum-size independent set, as described above, the two problems are not equivalent in an approximation-preserving way: The Independent Set problem has *no* constant-factor approximation unless **P** = **NP**.
